Credit Card Fraud Detection

Abstract

We detect anomalous behavior in credit card transactions using the dataset. In the dataset, there are 492 anomalies out of 284,807 transactions, and each transaction is described by 30 features and 1 label. Among the 30 features, there are 28 features transformed by PCA and 2 (non-transformed) features “Time” and “Amount”. The label “Class” is denoted by 1 if the transaction is a fraud, and 0 otherwise. Since the dataset is highly imbalanced, the \(F_{1}\) score is used.

The problem can be solved by supervised learning and anomaly detection. For the supervised learning, the dataset will be divided into 3 parts: 60% normal and oversampling anomalous transactions for training (or undersampling normal and 60% anomalous transactions for training), 20% normal and 20% anomalous transactions for cross-validation, and the rest 20% normal and 20% anomalous transactions for testing. For the anomaly detection, 60% normal transactions for training, 20% normal and 50% anomalous transactions for cross-validation, and the rest 20% normal and 50% anomalous transactions for testing. In particular, we will use logistic regression with regularization and Gaussian models. The results are summarized as follows.

resSupervised = data.frame("Supervised Model"=c("Logistic Regression with Oversampling","Logistic Regression with Undersampling"),
                     "Regularized Parameter"=c(0,2010),
                     Precision=c(0.06,0.92),
                     Recall=c(0.919,0.808),
                     F1=c(0.115,0.86))
print(resSupervised)
resAnomaly = data.frame("Anomaly Detection"=c("Gaussian","Multivariate Gaussian","Multivariate Gaussian"),
                     Features=c("All","All","Some"),
                     Threshold=c(1.609*10^(-114),1.323*10^(-142),1.007*10^(-52)),
                     Precision=c(0.311,0.568,0.917),
                     Recall=c(0.366,0.732,0.764),
                     F1=c(0.336,0.639,0.834))
print(resAnomaly)

The performance of the multivariate Gaussian model with selected features is close to the one using logistic regression with regularization trained on undersampling normal dataset. However, the former model requires selecting features carefully. By using logistic regression with regularization, we are able to refine a subset of features; and then we apply multivariate Gaussian model on the refined dataset.

Note that we implement logistic regression with regularization, Gaussian and Multivariate Gaussian models in R, and algorithms to select the regularized parameter and probability threshold using the evaluation metric on a cross-validation set.

The data

# Further select features among the above subset of features, where m is the number of elements in the subset denoted by m-subset, and size is the number of samples randomly chosen from all m-subsets.
selectFeature = function(X, Xval, yval, m, size) {
  bestCols = 0
  bestF1 = 0
  F1 = 0
  A = combn(1:ncol(X), m)
  idx = sample(1:ncol(A), size)
  for (j in idx) {
    l = A[,j]
    L = estimateMultiGaussian(X[,l])
    mu = L[[1]]
    Sigma = L[[2]]
    pval = multivariateGaussian(Xval[,l], mu, Sigma)
    L = selectThreshold(yval, pval, stepsize = 10^2)
    epsilon = as.numeric(formatC(L[[1]], format = "e", digits = 2))
    
    n=200
    f1Scores = rep(0, n)
    epsilons = rep(0, n)
    for (i in 1:n) {
      cvPredictions = ifelse(pval<epsilon*10^(-i), 1, 0)
      f1Scores[i] = F1(yval, cvPredictions)[[3]]
      epsilons[i] = epsilon*10^(-i)
    }
    
    cvPredictions = ifelse(pval<epsilons[which.max(f1Scores)], 1, 0)
    newF1 = F1(yval, cvPredictions)[[3]]
    
    if (newF1 > F1) {
      bestCols = colnames(X[,l])
      bestF1 = newF1
      F1 = newF1
    }
  }
  return(list(bestCols=bestCols, bestF1=bestF1))
}
